🔍 SOC Analyst Project: Email Legitimacy Investigation via WHOIS & DNS
📌 Overview

This project simulates a real-world Security Operations Center (SOC) investigation aimed at determining the legitimacy of an email sender.

Using a structured approach, I analyzed email headers and performed open-source intelligence (OSINT) techniques—including WHOIS lookups, DNS record analysis (via both Dig and PowerShell), and threat intelligence checks—to verify the authenticity of a domain and its supporting infrastructure.

This workflow reflects a core SOC responsibility in identifying phishing attempts and validating suspicious emails.

🛠️ Tools Used
Email Header Analysis: Manual inspection
WHOIS Lookup: whois command-line utility
DNS Lookup:
dig (Linux/Mac/WSL)
PowerShell Resolve-DnsName (Windows)
Threat Intelligence Platforms:
VirusTotal
AbuseIPDB
📋 Key Investigation Details
Target Domain: quora.com
Sending IP: 18.214.110.142
DKIM Signature: d=quora.com | s=pigeon
Analysis Date: (01-09-2025)
🧪 Methodology & Workflow

I followed a structured five-step process to assess the legitimacy of the email:

1. Extract Key Data from Email Headers

The investigation began with parsing raw email headers to extract key indicators:

From Domain: quora.com
Received Headers: Identified originating IP (18.214.110.142)
DKIM Signature: Domain (d=quora.com) and selector (s=pigeon)

📸 Screenshot Suggestion: Email header analysis

2. Perform WHOIS Lookup

Goal: Validate domain ownership and registration credibility

whois quora.com

Key Findings:

Registration Date: 1999
Registrar: CSC Corporate Domains, Inc. (enterprise-grade registrar)
Registrant: Verified corporate ownership

Conclusion:
A long-standing domain with transparent registration details is a strong indicator of legitimacy.

📸 Screenshot Suggestion: WHOIS output

3. Execute DNS Record Analysis

Goal: Validate email authentication mechanisms and infrastructure

To ensure accuracy, I used two approaches:

Method A: Using dig
# Mail Servers
dig quora.com MX +short

# SPF Records
dig quora.com TXT +short | grep spf

# DKIM Public Key
dig pigeon._domainkey.quora.com TXT +short

# DMARC Policy
dig _dmarc.quora.com TXT +short
Method B: Using PowerShell
Resolve-DnsName quora.com -Type MX
Resolve-DnsName quora.com -Type TXT
Resolve-DnsName _dmarc.quora.com -Type TXT
Resolve-DnsName pigeon._domainkey.quora.com -Type TXT

Key Findings:

SPF: Present and properly configured
DKIM: Valid public key identified (pigeon selector)
DMARC: Policy implemented
IP Authorization: Sending IP aligned with SPF records

Conclusion:
The domain demonstrates a strong and properly configured email authentication framework.

📸 Screenshot Suggestion: DNS/PowerShell output

3.5 Infrastructure Mapping with DNSDumpster

Goal: Identify related infrastructure and potential anomalies

Using dnsdumpster.com, I mapped the domain’s hosting environment.

Key Findings:

Hosted on a major cloud provider (expected for large platforms)
Associated subdomains (e.g., o50.pigeon.quora.com) appeared legitimate
No suspicious IP neighbors identified

Conclusion:
Infrastructure is consistent with a legitimate enterprise environment.

📸 Screenshot Suggestion: DNSDumpster results

4. Conduct Reputation Checks

Goal: Validate findings against threat intelligence sources

Queried domain and IP on VirusTotal and AbuseIPDB

Findings:

No malicious detections
Clean reputation across multiple vendors

